{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3bfa7c6c-31bf-4fe7-b3e7-e743d203e442","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports — no `createdump` needed:\n\n1. **Crash reports** are saved to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` files named after your process (e.g., `YourApp-2026-05-18-*.ips`).\n\n2. **Core dumps** — macOS disables them by default. To enable for future crashes:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n   Cores land at the path specified by `kern.corefile`.\n\n3. **Console.app** — you can also browse crash reports in the macOS Console app under *Crash Reports*.\n\nThe `.ips` crash log contains the native backtrace with frame addresses. If you need to symbolicate the .NET runtime frames in that `.ips` file, let me know — I can help with that too.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1f020602-aa75-42e8-921f-ef58426b3952","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app that crashed on macOS, without createdump available. This is a diagnostic question about .NET crash dumps on macOS.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of macOS crash reporting and .NET NativeAOT.","outputTokens":320,"requestId":"680A:247A30:C8F9E6:D621C8:6A0B0097"},"id":"ef474a39-03cf-4b69-9bf2-1e2a9a61b9fb","timestamp":"2026-05-18T12:05:57.474Z","parentId":"e2993f09-06cb-4aef-8753-0830ae15a06c"}
